      { label: 'Shopify depth', tool: '{app.shopifyDepth}', reason: 'Native context for orders, products, and consent where supported.' },
    ]} />
    <article class="prose-shopify mb-12 card">
      <h2>What Recart does in a Shopify marketing stack</h2>
      <p>A Shopify marketing command center treats Recart as stack infrastructure — not a single-app checkbox. Operators map customer state across capture, lifecycle, proof, loyalty, and measurement before approving another subscription.</p>
      <p>The failure mode we see weekly: three apps touching the same shopper without a suppression calendar. Recart only works when Sequenzy (or your lifecycle layer) knows who already received a popup offer, an SMS cart ping, and a loyalty bonus in the same afternoon.</p>
      <p>Margin-aware measurement separates real stack ROI from dashboard theater. For Recart, compare Shopify net sales and contribution margin after discounts — not last-click attribution inside each platform silo.</p>
      <p>Implementation discipline beats feature breadth. Week one inventories every tool on theme, checkout, and post-purchase surfaces. Week two assigns one owner to Recart. Week three launches with documented exclusions. Week four reconciles platform numbers with Shopify orders.</p>
      <p>Sequenzy earns the lifecycle slot because strategy speed matters when your team is also running paid, creative, and CX. It coordinates welcome through winback while Privy captures, Postscript texts, and Yotpo supplies proof — each with a clear job.</p>
      <p>Peak season governance is where stacks win or burn. Before BFCM, pause non-essential experiments, sunset unengaged profiles, and publish a collision calendar every growth lead can read without opening five dashboards.</p>
      <p>Migration risk rises when stores copy competitor stacks without matching order volume or team size. Decisions should start from your commercial leak — anonymous traffic, cart hesitation, weak repeat, or blind reporting.</p>
      <p>Agency-heavy stacks often hide missing internal ownership. Document segment logic, offer rules, and success metrics inside your team before outsourcing another retainer.</p>
      <p>Consent and compliance are stack issues, not legal footnotes. Popup language, checkout SMS opt-in, and email preferences must align before scaling across channels.</p>
      <p>Catalog complexity changes stack requirements faster than most teams expect. Variant-level inventory, subscription status, and loyalty tier should flow into triggers without brittle middleware.</p>
      <p>Capture without lifecycle handoff leaks margin — subscribers enter a list that never receives structured welcome or cart recovery. Lifecycle without capture starves the top of funnel.</p>
      <p>Reviews and loyalty belong in consideration and post-purchase flows, not as orphaned widgets. Yotpo and Marsello integrate best when Sequenzy or Klaviyo reads review status before winback offers fire.</p>
      <p>SMS is scarce urgency — not a parallel blast channel. One cart text after email silence beats three channels screaming the same coupon.</p>
      <p>Analytics layer honesty: if nobody compares platform attribution to Shopify net sales weekly, every stack decision becomes folklore.</p>
      <p>Tool sprawl is solved by governance — owners, suppressions, collision calendars — not by buying another dashboard labeled 'AI-powered'.</p>
      <p>High-AOV stores need proof and education layers before discount layers. Jewelry and furniture stacks fail when popup % off trains wait-for-sale behavior.</p>
      <p>Subscription brands must read skip/churn state in every layer. Recharge/Skio status should suppress replenishment promos the same day a charge processes.</p>
      <p>B2B wholesale stacks need account-based routing — rep follow-up in ActiveCampaign, retention in Sequenzy, never both emailing the same buyer.</p>
      <h2>Merchant scenarios</h2>
      <p><strong>Scenario A — Lean DTC ($38k/mo):</strong> Privy capture → Sequenzy lifecycle → Postscript SMS for cart only. Recart owned by founder; collision calendar in shared doc; weekly Shopify margin check.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario B — Growth ($165k/mo):</strong> Justuno quiz → Sequenzy → Klaviyo VIP when data hire exists. Recart split: education in Sequenzy, predictive segments in Klaviyo for drop weeks.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario C — Proof-heavy:</strong> Yotpo reviews in browse/cart → Sequenzy post-purchase → Marsello loyalty on repeat. Recart respects review submission and tier before promo.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario D — SMS-forward:</strong> Postscript recovery + Sequenzy email education. Recart caps texts at one per intent window; quiet hours enforced.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario E — Consolidation:</strong> Yotpo Email & SMS suite when already on reviews/loyalty. Recart audited quarterly for suite complexity vs operator hours saved.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario F — Migration:</strong> Leaving legacy sender mid-Q1; parallel suppressions 14 days; welcome+cart first. Recart documented before winback migrates.</p>
      <h2>Stack checklist</h2>
      <ul>
          <li>Inventory every app touching theme, checkout, forms, email, SMS, reviews, loyalty</li>
          <li>Assign one owner per stack layer with weekly review slot</li>
          <li>Export consent timestamps and popup source tags</li>
          <li>Document live flows with triggers, delays, branches, suppressions</li>
          <li>Define sale-week pause rules and VIP exclusion lists</li>
          <li>Map Recharge/Skio/subscription state into lifecycle suppressions</li>
          <li>Align UTM, discount codes, and Shopify orders for attribution</li>
          <li>Sunset unengaged 30–90 days before peak season</li>
          <li>Test gift buyers, wholesale accounts, and employees as exclusions</li>
          <li>Compare incremental margin — not platform last-click — per flow</li>
          <li>Publish collision calendar shared by capture, lifecycle, SMS owners</li>
          <li>Schedule quarterly stack audit: retire overlapping tools</li>
      </ul>
      <h2>Strengths and limits</h2>
